;B[sq]LB[rr:1][qr:2][pp:3][sq:4][qs:A]C[Diagram 3 (Alive in Pik)


It is a careless move for white to connect with 1.

Black 2 is a good move that applies the proverb stating, "the enemy's key point is your own".

If white plays 3, black plays 4 and lives in pik.

Instead of 3, if white plays at 4, it just allows black to live with more points when black plays \b\f1 A\b0\f0 .
